 To find the remainder of the expression $(n + 2)(n + 4)(n + 6)$ when divided by 7, we can use the given condition that $n \equiv 2 \pmod{7}$. This means that $n$ can be expressed as $7k + 2$ for some integer $k$.

Substituting this expression for $n$ into the given expression, we get:
\begin{align*}
(n + 2)(n + 4)(n + 6) &= (7k + 2 + 2)(7k + 2 + 4)(7k + 2 + 6) \ \\
 &= (7k + 4)(7k + 6)(7k + 8) \ \text{mod 7} \ \\
 &= 4 \cdot 6 \cdot 8 \ \text{mod 7} \ \\
 &= 2 \cdot 4 \cdot 1 \ \text{mod 7} \ \boxed{{2}}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the remainder when $(n + 2)(n + 4)(n + 6)$ is divided by 7 is 2.
